I finally got my hands on the highly anticipated Framework 13 laptop and built it from the ground up. While the concept of a fully upgradeable and repairable laptop is exciting, the reality left me with mixed feelings about its value proposition. In this video, I break down the pros and cons of the Framework 13, exploring whether its modularity justifies its premium price tag and older hardware.

Chapter Titles:
0:00 What is Framework?
2:27 Ridge
3:55 Unboxing
5:19 Build
12:56 Hardware
14:27 Price
17:17 Conclusion

1,5 years ago I decided in favor of buying a Yoga 7. Now I have multiple cracks on the plastic bezel around the screen and the plastic is shattered around both hinges. Even though I'm not a heavy duty user and mainly use it at home. Warranty repair denied claiming its due to physical damage (no it's not). Paying for the repair from my pocket, which requires replacing the entire screen section, would cost 70% of the original purchase cost.

Looking around I could hardly find any matte 2,8K display laptops on the market where I live and I'm aiming for that due to switching to Linux and needing a display without fractional scaling. The only other options I was able to find are a couple of Lenovos - Ideapad Pros and Yoga 7 Slims - priced between $1100-1400. Or some Lenovo T14s around $2200. Compared to these the Framework is not a bad deal at all, especially factoring in the repairability.

The only valid downside I agree with is the rounded corners on the screen offered only with squared bezels. I mean it just seems so straightforward to create bezels with the same rounded corners around the edges that I can't even fathom why Framework hasn't been doing it.
Thanks for the video. I will be getting a new laptop soon and it will be a framework.

He‚Äôs ABSOLUTELY RIGHT, so why have I paid my final payment for the even more expensive Intel Core Ultra version?

It‚Äôs because he underestimates the true value proposition that the Framework 13 offers.

Firstly, he‚Äôs misunderstood the true cost: all he talks about is the upfront cost, when it‚Äôs the savings on upgrade that redress the balance. 

E.g. to upgrade to the Ryzen 5 motherboard in his video it costs just $419.  This gives an indication as to what I can expect in future‚Ä¶that‚Äôs a bargain!!  Plus, as Framework grows in popularity, economies of scale should push the price down.

Secondly, when you upgrade your motherboard, you can repurpose your old motherboard eg as a server and there are free downloadable 3D printer case designs for Framework motherboards. 

Therefore, upon upgrading I get TWO computers not one new one‚Ä¶you need to add in the price of a free secondhand computer/server into the equation.

Thirdly, computers break..it‚Äôs a fact of life and the cost of repair is negligible with Framework compared to any other brand‚Ä¶and some brands are impossible to repair which means you have to replace the ENTIRE LAPTOP.  This huge cost is missing from his analysis.

Fourthly, he doesn‚Äôt properly factor the value of recycling and waste prevention‚Ä¶he‚Äôs just another mindless consumer who moans about the environment but does nothing about it even when the solution is in his hands.  The cognitive dissonance is palpable but he dismisses it. 

Lastly, as a Linux user, it‚Äôs fantastic to have a brand that‚Äôs put support of Linux as a primary goal.
It looks too pre-built to be called a byo laptop in my opinion.

LPCAMM2 looks like it is mainly for pro & gaming PCs due to the size, but maybe they will work, although they are currently 2-3X more expensive and upgrading 16GB to 32GB means you have to buy a 32GB CAMM2 board rather than just add 16GB.

"There are some downsides" to a laptop I can repair myself on a flight at 5am in the morning in time to make a 9am meeting at my destination? The kind of downsides that mean I can (and have) upgraded it MULTIPLE times over the last three years while saving hundreds of dollars? I buy what I need especially an ultrabook for most users that do not need to upgrade regularly as their workflow is constant (different for gamers and professional users). And I have an M1 MB Pro 13 that is nearly four years old with zero issues and remains more capable than the latest from Framework, especially in efficiency. I think many Framework fans believe they still live in the 1980s where laptops breakdown. These days if you look after your laptop they will easily last 5+ years. I have a working Intel MB Pro 15 that is now 8+ years old and still runs well.

@@andyH_England you're in the minority. The problem isn't about a MacBook "running well" after 8 years. The problem is the complete and utter inability to upgrade an ultrabook form factor laptop (which the FW13 is) down the road 3-5 years from now when better components and newer hardware are available.

@@spdcrzy I do not care about upgrading, nor do most non-techies. My 80-year-old parents have laptops and would never even think about upgrading. When you ramble on about upgrading, you are speaking as if the average person cares‚Äîthey don't, and Apple knows this. We see most OEMs now understanding that the new youth who have grown up with non-upgradeable tablets and phones do not care as much as children of the 20th century who got excited about upgrading.

‚Äã@@andyH_England "We see most OEMs now understanding that the new youth who have grown up with non-upgradeable tablets and phones do not care as much as children of the 20th century who got excited about upgrading."

You saying this tells me you have no idea what you are talking about. we, the new generation is all about upgradability and repairability, we do not want to throw things away and buy a completely new laptop just for the sake of it. we do not want to throw away a perfectly solid piece of tech just because of a faulty non upgradable ram or a bad Key in a non-replaceable keyboard. there is a reason we have tonnes of MacBook and think pads in the refurbished market because enterprises have to upgrade it because of non-upgradability.

If you buy a 3-year-old MacBook, create a new account, and try to install Keynote, or pages, they are not supported. i learned that the hard way. Even simple essential programs are not supported in old MacBooks. its basic software. how stupid is that?

Please for the love of God, do not speak on behalf of the "new youth" or the younger generation, you have no clue what you are talking about. you are in the minority.

@@swapnilmankame If you use a laptop for three years and then upgrade, why do you think the old laptop is e-waste? You can sell it, pass it on to family, donate to charity or send to an OEM for recycling. People that advocate the Framework always use this poor excuse. It is nonsense. Even if you break it after three years it can easily be recycled.

The new Huawei XT costs $3000 and yet in non-upgradeable so why is it one rule for one $3000 device and one rule for a $1000 laptop? I understand the true reason for upgradeability, to buy a base model and save money upgrading. But you can do that with some OEMs already like Lenovo. It only costs $100 to upgrade from 16GB to 64GB for their X Elite laptops. Probably cheaper than Framework. Same with storage.

We have strayed off the topic, that Framework is expensive and niche and that their future in such a competitive market is high risk. Hopefully they will survive, but if you read most of the comments, people understand that it is a lifestyle choice rather than a sensible value choice. That's fine if Framework still exists in 3-5 years time.
@@andyH_England right to repair is about more than just upgrading. It's about the ability to fix things yourself when - not if, WHEN - things fail. Because nothing is perfect. Not even a MacBook.

@@spdcrzy yes, right to repair is a noble notion but a better policy would be to get OEMs to improve quality and reliability. By making everything modular and easy to fix, you slow down that notion. We have seen with smartphones how non-upgradability has improved the ruggedness and toughness of smartphones. I can imagine in the future devices that rarely break down and are super durable. That should be where we aim for, rather than the right to repair as we shouldn't need to fix anything in the not too distant future.
@@andyH_England this is such a stupid take I'm not even going to respond to it. This is what underpins the "you will own nothing and be happy about it" mentality.

‚Äã@@andyH_EnglandThis is such an interesting thread to read through. As a framework user, I found your points thought-provoking, thank you for sharing.

From what i understood, your main points were 3:

1. durability and longevity is better than and should be prioritized over repairability;
2. Unused products can be sold refurbished or recycled by OEMs, so don't necessarily produce e-waste;
3. Only a niche minority group care about repairability and upgradability, and this attitude seems to be inconsistent.

Is this a fair understanding? I'll proceed assuming so.

First, regarding e-waste, I've actually read that it's really hard to fully recycle devices. Specifically what i was reading is that Apple, who have the lead, is able to recycle 60-80% of their iphones, only because they've invested loads into this and because they have only a small selection of models...

Second, regarding upgradability, the issues i run into old devices go beyond ram and storage. Batteries fail, screen technology improves, usb ports break, keyboard keys get stuck... The appeal of a machine like framework is that you can repair or upgrade almost every individual part without needing to ship your laptop away or pay a technician or pay for parts you don't really need replaced... Lenovo, Dell and other companies don't allow for this. They also don't allow for CPU upgrades. Why do i need a new keyboard, chassy, speakers, and screen if I just want a more powerful CPU? What about standard upgrades (e.g. you can't install a ddr5 ram on an old laptop that only supports ddr4)... The list goes on.

I agree that this isn't something someone's parents would necessarily care about. But businesses? Perhaps...

Lastly, though, and most importantly, Framework is trying their hardest to make the upgrades and repairs accessible to everyone. My dad got into engineering by taking apart things like TVs, radios, caset players, and putting them back together. This is no longer possible. People have become entirely dependent on the benevolence of OEMs and companies. It's demoralizing, disempowering, and a hindrance to meaningful learning...

I agree, realistically, probably nobody will care. But I hope framework computers are able to encourage people to open up their devices for the first time and have a poke around, even if they never would have normally dared. I'm sure as heck not risking breaking the water sealing on my phone trying to get it open, or breaking sth because i didn't melt the binding glue properly...

As for the durability vs repairability point, I don't have any thoughts beyond wondering if the two really are mutually exclusive...

‚Äã@@spdcrzyas mentioned above, i found this such an interesting thread to read through.

Based on my comment to andy, i think it's clear I'm leaning towards the "right to repair" side of things. Yet, I found Andy's argument that it's better to have durable things quite thought-provoking, personally.

So, I was wondering if you were willing to share why you felt it was a "stupid" take?

I agree that all things are bound to fail at some point, and being able to get in and fix it yourself significantly extends its life. But beyond that i am struggling to marshal my thoughts... Does this come at the expense of durability? Does advocating for repairability give companies an excuse to become sloppy with their quality? Obviously needing to swap out something constantly because it's low quality isn't good either...

I don't know, looking for thoughts :)

@@greatday19 The quality of a product is independent of whether it's been designed to be repaired properly. Planned obsolescence IS a thing, and Apple is a prime example of this. Whether or not their products are durable and high quality is irrelevant because, as with all tech, things WILL break. And WHEN they break, they are impossible to fix. Framework proved, in their very first generation product (which the FW13 was), that if they could make a user-repairable laptop for only a small price premium, manufacturers a hundred times larger than them with access to economies of scale have no excuse NOT to. The only reason OEMs don't make high-quality equipment that can be self-repaired - regardless of product category, be it cars, laptops, phones, washers, even CLOTHING - is because they don't want to. It's as simple as that. If they did, they could sell it at an obscene price and it would STILL make money. The OEMs simply don't want YOU to be able to dig into your own property. That's what "you will own nothing and be happy" means.

@@greatday19 Thanks for your response and although they are interesting, my arguments are as follows:

You cannot become 100% recycle-proof overnight. It is a work in progress, and Apple is getting closer to its 2030 deadline of being carbon neutral and having less e-waste. I prefer companies to take this approach rather than the Framework model, which ultimately will lead to lower profits, less investment and a lack of innovation.

Other parts failing: I have been using computers for forty years, and this has not happened more than a couple of times, and that was way back when. Reliability and durability are now excellent, assuming you care for your device. My original iPad still works!

I stand by my thoughts on "who cares?". There is a demographic we see in comments all the time that loves opening up their device and playing around with it. Personally, I don't think Framework is for "hardcore enthusiast", as Austin has claimed. 
I am not a computer enthusiast, and I love my framework. Here is my criteria for a good laptop:

- I only do very light computing task on my laptop, and I want good battery life, so U chip is actually an advantage for me, compare to the HS chip.
- I want my laptop to have minimal environmental impact. It should be long-lasting and produces minimal e-wastes.
- I want my laptop to have excellent Linux support, since I do not enjoy tinkering with my computers (happy to say, never `demsg`ed on my framework!)
- I want a knowledgeable support community that actually knows about computers, so that if anything actually failed, I know I can resolve it in a couple of days at most.
- I want long-term and easy firmware update for security. 
- If possible, I would prefer a nice screen.

I think my requirement embodies basically what "non-enthusiast" wants: "just works", good battery life, great support, basic security, and climate conscious. And this basically rules out most laptops out there. Most major laptop brands like Dell, HP and Lenovo all have terrible phone tree, and good luck finding anyone that actually knows what they are doing. Many of them also don't support automatic firmware update. I am not going to search for the firmware and flash it every month, that is simply not what a "non-enthusiast" would do.
In the end, the only manufactures that come close to framework are system76 and tuxedo. I eventually chose framework because of its nice 3:2 display, the upgradable CPU, and the U instead of HS processor.

Quite ironically, I believe Austin dislikes the framework precisely because he is an "enthusiast", he knows the performance differences between every laptop, and their value propositions. I personally would much prefer to not waste time in a phone tree or go on to dell forum, just to know that they are not able to fix my issue blah blah blah. With a framework, you know that all the hardware will work on Linux, with long-term support; and if anything fails, there is a huge and knowledgeable community that can help me fix it quickly.

The fact that Apple is one of the largest laptop manufacture, before their ARM transition, is a clear signal that consumers, especially non-enthusiasts like me, prefers a computer that works, instead of min-maxing on all the values on a laptop that will not be supported after a year. And I think that is the main target audiences of Framework.

And unfortunately, the framework laptop doesn't even have an upgradable CPU, it has a BGA (Ball grid array) socket just like any laptop made in the past decade (Not that it ever could since neither Intel nor AMD produce any PGA (pin grid array) laptop CPUs anymore), which means to replace the CPU, you would need to replace the whole motherboard.

And if you've seen the prices on their site, it becomes pretty clear why nobody ever really talks about upgrading their Framework's CPUs. Their motherboards are wholly expensive, costing upwards of a half of the value of the laptop, mostly because of the "framework tax", but also because a motherboard contains like 90% of the brains of a laptop, which is why the Framework laptop is just as un-upgradable (at least when it comes to the CPU) as any other laptop on the market.

There is one thing I'll applaud Framework on though, and that's the fact that they have replacement parts readily available, which is not so much the case for most consumer models of other brands.

Ok so, I am not one to comment often but I feel your comparison to the Lenovo to be way off, for several reasons, and it does Framework a great disservice.
And as someone that has been looking in the farthest corners for a laptop that suits me and my needs, I have looked at this Lenovo already, and the specs are horribly misleading on the product page.

The Lenovo you showed had the following specs (model: 83DK000DUS, Model number shown at 16:54)
 - Ryzen 5 8640HS (a little bit quicker than the Ryzen 5 7640U, sure)
 - 8GB of completely non-upgradeable RAM (Yes, I double-checked, you need to order enough when you buy it, Lenovo explicitly lists it as Soldered LPDDR5)

 - a 512GB SSD (likely a cheaper offering than those from Framework, which are WD Black model drives, the SN770 or SN850X)
 - a "2k" display, bonus being touch (Lenovo lists it as a 1920x1200 300nit 60Hz IPS panel, which is NOT even close to the 2.8k 2880x1920 500nit 120HZ display you got on the Framework)
 - The Lenovo is a 2-in-1 model which IS a bonus, sure
 - You compared the Lenovo at its sale price, of $450, which it is no longer on sale and is $750

So, a better comparison would be an HP Pavilion Plus 14Z-EY100 with the 1TB upgrade, which has an MSRP of $1120 for the Ryzen 5 with 16GB of RAM and a 2560x1600 120hz IPS 300nit display or $1260 for the Ryzen 7 with 16GB of RAM and the 2880x1800 120hz 400-500nit OLED display, I am sure there are other similar comparisons, but it is one I have found during my searching.

I love the content Austin but please make sure your due diligence is done for something like this, as the Framework and Lenovo are in completely different categories (a higher end version of the same Lenovo model would make a better comparison instead). There are really two types of laptop users: those who get a new one every 2-3 years and those who invest in something that‚Äôll last. I‚Äôm definitely in the latter camp. The cost to replace the battery was so high that buying a new laptop seemed like a better option. Film student here! Typically, when it comes to scripts, a general rule of thumb is one page of a script equals 1 minute in the final film, so if we're looking at the pages from a story perspective, placing them into a cohesive story... I'd say either the 3rd or 4th one flow the best, not saying that the others aren't likely either... but they do flow the best. 

For the 3rd one, Mike burning plushies in sort of a co-op mission could lead to a climax and resolution at the end of the film given it's page 58, making it around an hour mark would leave enough time for a resolution. 

Similar reasoning for the 4th one, this sequence would be early on in the film... possibly being an event from the past, which would then connect somehow to something later in the movie. 

The reason I don't think the 1st one is likely is because based on where Vanessa was left off in the first film, how likely is it that she's out of the hospital... there could be a time jump, perhaps she was watching Abby and they were kidnapped by an animatronic... but the suspense in the scene just seems too much for what would be the half hour mark in what will probably be close to a 2 hour film. 

As for the 2nd one... it's just a bit much in all honesty. This scene seems what is typically exposition, giving the audience some backstory... and it's just unusual to place this in 20 minutes in. Then again, this is Scott we're talking about... and perhaps we meet these characters earlier in the film... but I can't imagine an event taking place that would even involve the US Government with Fazbear Entertainment this early on, if at all in the franchise. 

I'm honestly happy to talk more about this too, disecting scripts is essentially what I study at school... ha!!

Hii, I'm a film graduate and I have some thoughts. This will be a LONG text (1114 words lol) explaining my opinion and I apologize if there's smth hard to understand (English isn't my first language) but, in a nutshell, I think the fourth and last script is the real one bc, from a narrative standpoint, it would make a good start for the movie AND it's written correctly (although not having numbered scenes is infuriating but alas, none of the scenes in other scripts are numbered, so maybe it's a weird standard from US filming industry, idk). 

I also think that "the man" can't be (or at least shouldn't be) any important character unlike Darrin and Gemma. Why? Well, when you hand the script to the actors and actresses, they need to know the role they are playing, so hiding the identity of the character in a script that only the staff would read and that everyone working on it knows who the character is is unnecessary and even confusing. A script is meant to guide the actors and describe ONLY what is shown on the screen objectively. 

I agree that it's weird that a dad goes into an abandoned Freddy's and KNOWS his way around (if he didn't, he wouldn't have known that the carousel has a door that leads to a staircase and wouldn't enter it without second thoughts) so my guess is that he's an employee from Freddy's, like a technician or smth similar. As to why he'd be bringing his kids to an abandoned location? Idk, maybe William ordered him to do so (either by manipulation or intimidation) or some other reason. I can imagine lots of possibilities tbh, but we won't know until the movie comes out.

But why am I so sure it's the last one? Well, I'm not 100% sure bc the third one is also very plausible to be real, but feels weird that in minute 58 of the movie (as others said down here in the comments, the numbering system of a script is 1 page is 1 minute of the film) Mike is getting ready to kinda sneak in a guarded location, either FNAF 2 location with the toy animatronics or somewhere else. The standard length for a movie is between 1h 30 min and 2h and, assuming that the film will be at least 2h, this is happening right in the middle of the film, which feels weird bc there would be 1h more of action when this feels like the start of the climax of the movie, which actually would make a bit more sense if the movie was around 1h 30 min. However, knowing that the first movie was 1h 50 min, I HIGHLY doubt that this one will be shorter bc there's A LOT more material than in the first one (for starters, there are twice as many animatronics than in the first movie that have to be narratively presented and developed and the budget of the movie is clearly a lot higher, so there's no way it will be shorter). So yeah, the third one just feels weird timing-wise.

About the second script... Well, I won't even touch the thing about remnant and government funding the pizzaplex BUT what definitively sent me off is that it's not written correctly. It might be considered nitpicking BUT as I said before, a script has to describe the actions seen on screen objectively, so the paragraph where the men and women at the table are "obviously surprised to hear that blah blah blah" is NOT an objective action. It's a description of the character's thought process and/or viewer interpretation and is a basic error in script writing. A script isn't a novel and has many rules concerning it's writing, and that's one of the basic ones that any of us film students granted us an F many times when we were starting to write scripts (I used to write novels, so I obviously learned this the hard way). Also, the annotations (the brief text under the name of the character's dialogue) are incorrect bc an annotation is an indication of the emotions or expressions that a character is doing like "(looks distressed)" or "(in a sad tone)" that are meant for the actor to understand the tone of the actions and dialogue they're doing. However, all the annotations in this script are actions like "waving a hand" or "thumping the paper", which are also written incorrectly bc ALL verbs have to be in a present tense, not in gerund bc those verbs are narrative, which I've already said that it's a no-go in script writing. So yeah, if this script is the real one, I'd be disappointed MAINLY bc that script is supposed to be written by a professional, and no professional should make such basic errors.

Finally, about the first script, for starters my brain hurts while trying to understand how the action is being presented, so that says a lot. Again, it's written like if it was a novel, which I said it's a basic error, but, aside from that, the action described is weird by itself. From a timing standpoint, this happening 25 min in the movie is simply weird: it has no flow of action purpose, feels really forced and basically this should happen either at the start of the movie where the plot conflict is presented, at the start of the climax deepening the conflict (Vanessa and Abby are tricked by William/other antagonist to do smth through Toy Chica) or at the end of the movie where the conflict is solved with a weirdly happy ending that wouldn't suit this franchise at all. Also, from a lore standpoint, it feels off that Toy Chica, out of all Toy animatronics, can talk so fluidly bc I don't remember the Toy animatronics having a complex voice box. That actually would fit more to what I remember about the Funtimes with the voice luring system and stuff. However, as literally no one else called this out, not even Dawko, I'm going to assume that I have the animatronics all mixed up.

So that would be my reasoning as to why I think the last script would be the more fitting to be an actual movie script. I just wish they number the scenes bc oh boy not numbering them just makes filming REALLY complicated for everyone in the set, and I'm talking through experience. Also, if you've read all this to the end omg you are crazy and thank you so much, I hope this was as educational for you as it was infuriating to me lol

I'm experienced with story structure and pacing in both screenplays and novels, and the two scripts you talked about at the very end are both very likely to be the real one!

Mystery is obviously a big part of most horror movies, so the one with the dad going to the pizzeria with his kids sounds like an extremely good set up and hook. However, it feels like the first three pages would either be crammed with info, or just barren/vague and confuse people.

The other script with Mike and Abby talking about the ‚Äúplushies‚Äù is probably referencing the story of the ‚ÄúVelveteen Rabbit‚Äù which I loved as a kid but am now disturbed by haha. The page number being in the 50‚Äôs range tells me that it is in the middle of the script (industry standard script length for most movies is around 80-120 pages, and 1 page = 1 Minute), aka where our heroes do something that will trigger the start of the final act. 

Make what you will of this, Thanks for reading!

My major worry is this movie is going a little too fast. I know that sounds insane after waiting eight years for the first movie, but hear me out here. The first movie was amazing, obviously, the props and animatronics were genuinely perfect. It was more just fantastic and wonderful and magical seeing this movie come to life before our eyes, but that doesn‚Äôt mean it was without problems. The first Fnaf movie suffered from pacing and lack of horror. There were a lot of scenes that just kind of jumped back-and-forth between each other with no connective tissue, some characters seem to bland, even though they were complex, just because they didn‚Äôt have enough screen time. And of course the lack of blood makes things frustrating. The springlocks scene could‚Äôve been so much better if we saw blood leaking out of the suit slowly. And obviously blood doesn‚Äôt equal horror, so, having more shots of the animatronics stalking the protagonists from the background in the darkness is necessary, keep them creepy, elevating dread to another level. I am absolutely excited about this movie, I just really hope they learn from their mistakes with the first one and make the best thing they possibly can.

Personally I believe that page 4 is the real one:

Page 25: As you said, it's a bit weird. Doesn't seem like a scene that would only be on page 25 of the film, and the tone seems very off.

Page 18: Most obviously fake one of the bunch. It's also a reference too one of the failed concepts for the first movie that scott told us about. Something regarding the army using Fazbear technology in the military or something.

Page 58: Def the 2nd most convincing one, however still probably fake. It seems like yet another reference to a failed concept, this one being the infamous "plushies take manhattan" pitch from years ago. Also Mike's line at the end doesn't seem in character for him. But your thoughts on the plushie story being an analogy is a very good point.

Page 4: Makes the most sense. This seems like a cold open to the film establishing that there was more than one location in the timeline. And the vagueness of the context of the scene makes it seem like it's real. The line "we're not here for a ride sweetie." shows a clear ulterior motive that would probably be set up in the next minutes of the script. Also it's the only one that references something from the actual fnaf 2 location and uses it as part of the story. Unlike page 25 which only references toy chica existing.

@@D3kKromb0x From what I recently read, NASA was considering going with only one contract, and that contract would have gone to Boeing, considering they are a veteran of the aerospace industry.

As it is, NASA awarded $4.2 billion to Boeing for Starliner, while giving SpaceX about $2.6 billion to develop Crew Dragon. Sierra Nevada's Dream Chaser was also a contender for the Commercial Crew Program, but ultimately lost out to Boeing and SpaceX (with NASA citing a "lack of maturity", whatever that means).

NASA felt that Boeing's proposal was the superior one, and that they would be able to get to the ISS first. Instead, Boeing ran over their budget by $1.5 billion, ended up way behind schedule (resulting in SpaceX beating them to the ISS by four years), and now this debacle, resulting in SpaceX having to come to the rescue.

With Starliner basically a lemon now, and rumors swirling that Boeing might shutter the program altogether, I bet some of the NASA officials are wondering if they should have gone with Dream Chaser instead. I know I would have.

If Boeing cannot fix the problems with Starliner and/or shutters the program, NASA might have no choice but to rescind Boeing's contract and go with another company. The best bet would probably be Dream Chaser from Sierra Space (spun off from Sierra Nevada into a fully independent company), especially if their inaugural launch next year goes well.

I just read a brief article saying that one of the reasons NASA does not want the two astronauts that went up in the StarLiner to return in a SpaceX capsule is that their Boeing-designed spacesuits cannot be used in a SpaceX capsule. It is true that the spacesuits for Starliner are not compatible with the Crew Dragon, and vice versa.  But now, it's been confirmed that Barry Wilmore and Sunita Williams are returning on a Crew Dragon anyway.  They will either return home unsuited (harkening back to the Apollo days, when the astronauts did that), or SpaceX will launch a couple of spacesuits to the ISS (if not on Crew-9, then another mission; maybe CRS-32, which is slated to launch in December).

@@astrofan1993 That's great that there is a workaround. But doesn't is seem ill advised to have two different spacesuit standards? I assume the differences are in things like hose, wiring, and tubing connections.

@@salemengineer2130 It's not just the hoses, wiring, and tubes, it's also the overall shape of the spacesuit itself. The Starliner spacesuit simply cannot fit into a seat on a Crew Dragon, as it's too bulky. SpaceX spacesuits are more sleek and modern, if not futuristic, while Starliner spacesuits are based on traditional 20th Century designs.

As it is, NASA still prefers Starliner over Crew Dragon to this day, even though Crew Dragon has outperformed all expectations for the last several years. So once the kinks for Starliner get worked out, I have a feeling that Starliner will become the workhorse of the Commercial Crew Program over SpaceX.

It would have been nice if NASA mandated some sort of compatibility between the two spacecraft, but I don't know if that crossed their mind. Even if it did, since both vehicles are of radically different designs, the spacesuits would have been designed differently as well, regardless of what NASA wanted.

In fact, the largest shareholders for Boeing (The Vanguard Group and BlackRock, Inc., amongst others) are the same largest shareholders for Kroger (which was the company I used to work for). Scott, I would propose an alternative explanation for the waffling of Boeing and the Leadership there.  Boeing has been led by leadership over the last couple of decades that has been very cavalier about safety vs. "the bottom line".  They have been caught up in massive lawsuits and bad press and don't at this point need any more of that.  They want to take the chance and send the astronauts home on the Starliner, buuuut the standard risk you talk about has suddenly become a more important and concern than previous due the sudden attack of risk aversion.  I think this is the more important issue and the bad press from keeping the Astronauts up there is much less than the risk of possible catastrophe on re-entry, as long as the potential for fixing the issues and lowering the risk on the Starliner re-entry.  Boeing has not previously been too risk averse in the Aircraft safety defects dropping planes out the skies and killing thousands of people, but the consequences of that attitude have been much more severe than they have calculated and planned for in their financial spreadsheet.  Just my personal opinion!  I personally think their best outcome would be to bring the Astronauts home on Dragon and send the Starliner home by itself.  If it fails re-entry, the leadership can claim good precautionary judgement and if it survives re-entry, they can claim good judgement in not risking the Astronauts.   The only other factor is what Boeing would consider is the embarrassment of having to be bailed out by Elon Musk, but I think their spinmeisters in their Company can spin this to mitigate the embarrassment factorf quite well.  Again, just my personal opinion.  Thanks for the opportunity to expound.

*Summary*

* *[**0:00**]* *Extended Stay:* Astronauts on Starliner face a potentially much longer stay on the ISS due to ongoing technical issues. An 8-day mission could turn into an 8-month one. 
* *[**1:16**]* *Contingency Plans:* NASA has backup plans ready if Starliner can't safely return the astronauts. Options include:
    * *[**1:47**]* Sending a Dragon spacecraft with only two astronauts instead of four, bringing the Starliner crew back after 6 more months on the ISS.
    * *[**2:08**]* Utilizing the cargo pallet on the Crew-8 Dragon for astronaut return.
* *[**2:34**]* *Safety Concerns:* NASA is hesitant about clearing Starliner for re-entry due to unresolved technical issues, prioritizing astronaut safety above all else. The upcoming US election adds another layer of pressure on decision-making. 
* *[**4:57**]* *Thruster Issues:* Five maneuvering thrusters underperformed during approach to the ISS. While four are now back online, the cause remains uncertain. 
* *[**7:01**]* *Potential Cause:* Boeing believes the issue might stem from Teflon seals inside the oxidizer poppets (valves). Overheating may have caused the seals to extrude, interfering with oxidizer flow.
* *[**9:18**]* *Blame Game:* This incident might spark another dispute between Boeing and Aerojet Rocketdyne (thruster manufacturer) regarding responsibility for the technical failure.  
* *[**5:56**]* *Software Concerns:* Configuration changes made to the software for crewed flight haven't been fully tested due to Boeing's cost-cutting measures. 
* *[**11:48**]* *Future Implications:* Even if Starliner returns without crew, Boeing could push for operational status, despite the need for technical fixes. However, the limited availability of Atlas V rockets for future launches poses a significant challenge.

Ah teflon. My prior company used huge teflon pipes as insulator for the high voltage side of electro static dust collectors. That worked well until reaching a fume temperature of about 220¬∞C. That's the reason, why teflon isn't a good sealing material when it involves heat! Better for that is the red coloured silicone, up to 350¬∞C or the black coloured high temp silicon up to a 1000¬∞C. It sounds like they have to upload all the guidance data for an unmanned return, if NASA decides they want to go with an un-manned return.  I'm sure the guidance-package is a very large set of files (at least relative to the ISS download speeds).  And, I'm guessing here, they probably would attempt to upload it directly to the Starliner - not go to a computer on-board then kick it over to a thumbdrive and install it that way.  I'm confident that, if they go the route of having to upload it the ISS and then transfer it to spacecraft manually, they will probably have to write a program to upload and install on the ISS onboard computer that can read the Boeing guidance-package (because it's certainly formatted in a protocol that their current computers cannot understand).  No matter how they do it - the file is going to have to get transferred (after it has been written, error-checked, debugged, and formatted for transfer) over the course of hours or days and will be tying up a lot NASA and the ISS's data-transfer resources for quite some time.  Then they are going to have to repeat the process in reverse to make sure the file they sent up was received, unpacked, and installed without any corruption.  Basically, they will need to make sure the file they get back is the same file as the one they sent up and the Starliner guidance system doesn't see anything it doesn't like and spit the whole thing back out.  If they can, I imagine they want to upload directly to the Starliner via it's onboard antennas - but, between the communications going between the ISS and ground and the fact that they are hanging out in the middle of the ionosphere - they are very likely to have major interference problems if this wasn't a contingency the Boeing guys planned on.

And, I hate dragging politics into it, but, one can imagine, that the sitting-VP has demanded a no BS number on the probabilities and if that no-BS number is higher than 1% the head of the National Space Council has almost certainly told NASA that she isn't authorizing a thing until after Nov. 5.  Not to mention, even if it fails without anyone onboard - Boeing's stock is going to plummet and EM is going to suddenly be worth a whole heck of a lot more money.

And, not to fuel any potential conspiracy theories (that's a lie - that's exactly what I'm about to do), if they opt to send it back un-manned and Boeing has a pretty good idea that the design-flaw that post-flight analysis would demonstrate is on them, they'd have a really strong financial incentive to see the thing burn up pretty good on re-entry.  They wouldn't want to make it seem like an unintended destruction of the vehicle (that would have terrible implications for Boeing stakeholders) the narrative would be something along the lines of - "after x-days on-orbit, we don't trust the thruster-performance enough to risk trying to align a precision re-entry with a landing-zone that we cannot fully guarantee. So, we've decided it's just safer to burn off every m/s of velocity we can with the propellent we've got and plow this thing straight down somewhere over the central Pacific."
Harris hasn't ever, and doesn't get involved in ANY day-to-day discussions. She believes the cloud data is up there somewhere in the sky for crying out loud.

Before any of the Thrusters, Doghouses, Poppets, etc. are ever built, every component is subject to a PDR (Preliminary Design Review) where NASA, Boeing, and The Sub Contractor  review, agree, and approve any design for a proposed component.  NASA and Boeing, will make suggestions for changes (based on their experts experience) to the proposed design with "action items" that have to be completed by the builder before manufacture of the component can start. The builder then manufactures the "First Article or Pathfinder" component which then is tested to the customer's requirements.  The results of the testing are then reviewed again by NASA and Boeing at a CDR (Critical Design Review).  The contractor is usually given another "action item" burn-down list to complete before any "Production Parts" can be manufactured.  In the case of any of the working components on Starliner, NASA, Boeing and the supplier were all in agreement before production of any Doghouse Components were ever built.  Usually the testing regimen far exceeds whatever expected operating conditions during a nominal flight usually by a multiple factor. In this case it sounds like the environmental testing that did occur, did not expose this weakness in the system.  There is lot more going on here than most people realize.

Software problems also arose early in the Apollo era. Margaret Hamilton discovered a potential problem with the Apollo Guidance Computer (AGC) when her daughter, who often accompanied her to work, was playing in a simulator. Her daughter accidentally selected a prelaunch program (P01) during a flight, something astronauts would normally never do. This incident led Hamilton to alert her superiors and advocate for more robust error handling mechanisms.

Although her warnings were initially ignored, it turned out that this very error had been made by James Lovell during the Apollo 8 mission.

Product: Rocket Boosters Mk VII
Rating: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ‚òÜ‚òÜ

Review Title: When You Need to Escape, But Only Slightly Faster

So, I bought these Rocket Boosters Mk VII thinking I'd finally have a way to beat rush hour traffic. Boy, was I wrong.

First off, the delivery. I get it, shipping rocket boosters isn't exactly the same as delivering a pair of socks, but three weeks? Really? By the time these showed up, I could have walked to the moon and back.

Unpacking these things was like opening the box to a new IKEA bookshelf, except instead of missing screws, I was missing crucial ignition components. I‚Äôm pretty sure I ordered boosters, not an expensive lawn ornament.

Once I managed to get them assembled (thanks to a few "how-to" videos from 12-year-old rocket enthusiasts on YouTube), I fired them up. Or at least I tried to. After a series of loud sputters and more smoke than a 90s grunge concert, they finally kicked in. The "boost" was more of a gentle nudge. Imagine getting a push on a swing from a toddler‚Äîyeah, that‚Äôs the kind of "thrust" we‚Äôre talking about.

And let‚Äôs talk about noise. If you ever wanted to simulate living next to a jet engine test facility, these are perfect. My neighbors are thrilled. I‚Äôm now known as the "weird rocket guy" in the neighborhood. Great.

The final straw? These things consume fuel like a college kid consumes ramen. I had to make five trips to the gas station just to keep them running for an hour. Not exactly economical for my great escape plans.

Overall, these boosters are more trouble than they're worth. Unless you're a masochist with a penchant for DIY frustration and an endless fuel budget, steer clear.

Moving a seat from one spacecraft has been done in the past; they moved Francisco Rubio's seat from Soyuz MS-22 to the Crew-5 Crew Dragon. Instead, I imagine to avoid embarrassing Roskosmos, NASA agreed to have Rubio remain on the ISS for an extra six months before returning on the replacement Soyuz MS-23. I am certain Rubio's wife Deborah was not amused! Note that if the Trashliner astronauts return on a Crew Dragon they cannot plug their Boing spacesuits into the life support system to handle the remote chance of a containment leak evacuating the capsule.

I am a little surprised that NASA is considering bringing Butch and Suni back on the Crew-9 capsule, which is currently already loaded and waiting at KSC for launch, rather than the Axiom-4 capsule which is to briefly visit the ISS in October. The Axiom capsule could get them back home in October 2024 instead of March 2025. The Axiom-4 capsule will be carrying a minimum of cargo because it is not a regular NASA resupply mission, which would permit sending up two extra SpaceX seats and two SpaceX spacesuits tailored to Butch and Suni. There just isn't time between now and the launch of Crew-9 to make any changes in the configuration but the two months between now and the Axiom launch should be entirely adequate. Also the Trashliner must be removed from the ISS before Crew-9 arrives because the Trashliner is occupying one of the two docking ports that are the SpaceX contribution to the ISS. The two other ports on the US side of the ISS are the original ports used by the Space Transportation System (STS aka Shuttle) and are now three decades old and used only by the Cygnus and Cargo Dragon supply capsules. Using SpaceX suits would be safer than having them wear their Boing spacesuits, because they could be plugged into the life support system.

‚Äã @ ThatOpalGuy profit is defined as revenue minus cost and dependent on supply vs demand state. If demand exceeds supply, the buyers will (happily) pay more than it cost for rare product. When supply exceeds demand it's the other way around.. So profits signal supply issues and are actually INCENTIVIZING additional suppliers to join - to increase the supply until it meets demand (at cost) - at which point the profit vanishes.

TL;DU: if the goal is (perpetual) profit it requires the control of the supply and COMPETING capitalists are the last that will achieve that. It requires Monopolists for this and support from the market authority in the form of rules that prohibit or undermine competition.

How do you avoid venemous snakes and spiders eg death adders

They just do what every young Australian living in or near the bush is taught: Wear thick leather boots, walk noisily, particularly in or near long grass or dense ground-level vegetation.
